3w.title: Arbital Markdown
3w.clickbait: All about Arbital's extended Markdown syntax.
3w.text:
[summary: This page lists non-standard Markdown syntax that's specific to Arbital. Learn how to insert MathJax, create smart links, set page's summary, add todos, etc...]

Arbital uses Markdown syntax for editing the pages. If you've used Reddit or StackOverflow, it's the same syntax. Here is a helpful [guide to Markdown syntax](http://mathoverflow.net/editing-help) on MathOverflow.

## LaTeX

You can use **\$\$** to create inline mathematical expressions, e.g. **\$\$ax^2 + bx + c = 0\$\$** will be displayed as: $ax^2 + bx + c = 0$  
And **\$\$\$** to create centered math expressions, e.g. **\$\$\$\lim_{N \to \infty} \sum_{k=1}^N f(t_k) \Delta t\$\$\$** will be displayed as: $$\lim_{N \to \infty} \sum_{k=1}^N f(t_k) \Delta t$$

## Special Arbital Markdown syntax

Arbital adds a few extra features to Markdown syntax.

### Smart links

You can quickly link to a page by using `[id]` or, even better, `[alias]` syntax. For example:  
`[3w]` => [3w]  
`[3w]` => [3w]

If you want the inserted title to be lower-cased, add a dash:  
`[5s]` => [5s]  
`[-5s]` => [-5s]

If you want to specify what text shows up as the link, use `[alias text]`. For example:  
`[3w Custom link]` => [3w Custom link]

If you link to a page that doesn't exist, the link will show up red:  
`[definitely_doesnt_exist Doesn't exist]` => [definitely_doesnt_exist Doesn't exist]

If you want to just create a red link with some text:  
`[ create a page for this concept later]` => [ create a page for this concept later]

If you want to mention someone use `[@userId]` or `[@userAlias]`:  
`[@1]` => [@1]  
`[@1]` => [@1]  
NOTE: the user will get an update if the mention is in a comment.

### Other

You can set the [1kl page's summary], which shows up in popovers and other places. For example:  
`[summary: Summary of the page goes here. *Markdown* is okay!]`  
Or to set a specific summary:  
`[summary(Technical): Very technical summary. *Markdown* is okay!]`    
Make sure that the entire summary block is in a paragraph of its own.

You can embed [3r votes] from other pages. For example:  
`[vote: 3r]` creates this voting bar:  
[vote: 3r]

You can leave "todo" markers for yourself or other authors. For example:  
`[todo: finish this section]` [todo: finish this section]  
`%%todo: this supports line breaks, but needs to be its own paragraph  
%%`  
This will not show up on the page in any way. Red links and "todo" markers count towards the todo score, which you will see next to the pages on the Explore and your Profile pages.
%%todo: this supports line breaks
%%

Similarly, you can leave comments for other authors, but without increasing the todo count. For example:  
`[comment: there has got to be a better metaphor for this]` [comment: there has got to be a better metaphor for this]  
`%%coment: this supports line breaks, but needs to be its own paragraph. You can vary the number of |s to envelop other similar blocks.  
%%`  
Again, this doesn't show up for the reader in any way.

%%comment: this supports line breaks, but needs to be its own paragraph. You can vary the number of |s to envelop other similar blocks.
%%
